solutions.content:
**Explanation:**
First, we iterate recursively through the tree to find the desired node.
Now, we have three cases when we want to delete a node:
1. It's a leaf
2. It has one child
3. It has two children

So the way we solve the problem for each case is:
1. A leaf - simplest, just point parent to NULL.
2. One child - make a bypass and point the parent to the child.
3. This case is a bit complicated. We need to make sure we keep the BST rules.
The algorithm is, we find either the smallest number larger than `key` or the largest number smaller than `key`. That way, if we replace the key with it, the BST won't break.
So I chose to find the smallest node larger than `key`. To get that, we go to the right child -> larger, then we go down to the leftmost leaf -> smallest in subtree.
We replace the original value with the value we found and then delete the node that we found (It has to have maximum one child because we went all the way down to the leftmost).
We call `deleteNode` recursively and now we have one of the easy cases.
```
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* leftmost(TreeNode* node) {
        while (node && node->left) node = node->left;
        return node;
    }

    TreeNode* deleteNode(TreeNode* root, int key) {
        if (!root) return NULL;

        if (key < root->val) root->left = deleteNode(root->left, key);
        else if (key > root->val) root->right = deleteNode(root->right, key);

        else {
            if (root->left == NULL) {
                TreeNode* tmp = root->right;
                delete root;
                return tmp;
            }

            else if (root->right == NULL) {
                TreeNode* tmp = root->left;
                delete root;
                return tmp;
            }

            else {
                TreeNode* tmp = leftmost(root->right);
                root->val = tmp->val;
                root->right = deleteNode(root->right, tmp->val);
            }
        }

        return root;
    }
};
```
