# Delete an node in a BST
* ## *Approach :*
1. search the key in BST. If the key is not there simply return root.
2. If key is present then we have 3 cases. They are
	1. 	If key has **no childs** (Leaf Node) then delete that node i.e  ` return NULL `.
	2. 	If key has **One child** then delete that node and replace with child node.
		 ` if(root->left==NULL) return root->right; `
		 ` if(root->right==NULL) return root->left; `
	3. If key has **Two childs** (Difficult and IMP) then replace with inorder successor and delete that node for inorder successor. Inorder Successor means left most node in right subtree.

* ## *Code :*
```
TreeNode* inordersuccessor(TreeNode* root){
        if(root->left==NULL) return root;
        return inordersuccessor(root->left);
    }
    TreeNode* deleteNode(TreeNode* root, int key) {
        if(root==NULL) return root;
        if(root->val > key){
            root->left = deleteNode(root->left,key);
        }
        else if(root->val < key){
            root->right = deleteNode(root->right,key);
        }
        else{
            if(root->left==NULL && root->right==NULL){
                return NULL;
            }
            if(root->left==NULL) return root->right;
            else if(root->right==NULL) return root->left;

            TreeNode* inSucc=inordersuccessor(root->right);
            root->val = inSucc->val;
            root->right = deleteNode(root->right,inSucc->val);
        }
        return root;
    }
```

* ## *Result :*
	85% Faster
