* Now we have to delete that Node. It means if we are not having left subtree then directly return the right subtree as well as vice-versa.
* But if we are having both subtree then we have to find the smallest Node in the right subtree which will be left most Node.

* Now replace the value of root Node with the lowest right subtree and Delete that Node.

**Implementation :**
'''

	class Solution:
    def deleteNode(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], key: int) -> Optional[TreeNode]:

        if root is None:
            return 

        if key<root.val:
            root.left = self.deleteNode(root.left,key)

        elif key>root.val:
            root.right = self.deleteNode(root.right,key)

        else:
            if root.left is None:
                return root.right

            if root.right is None:
                return root.left

            tmp = root.right
            mini= tmp.val
            while tmp.left!=None:
                tmp = tmp.left
                mini= tmp.val
            root.val = mini
            root.right = self.deleteNode(root.right,root.val)

        return root

