**✅ IF YOU LIKE THIS SOLUTION, PLEASE UPVOTE.**
****
This solution employs counting of character frequencies followed by either sorting the original string or constructing a new one. Time complexity is linear: **O(N)**. Space complexity is linear: **O(N)**.
****

**Comment.** Character frequencies can be used in at least two ways:
1. As a comparator key for a sorting function.
2. As a length of each single-character chunk of the result.

This results in the following approaches to the problem.

**Python #1.** One-liner. Counter + construction.
```
class Solution:
    def frequencySort(self, s: str) -> str:
        return "".join(c * ch for c, ch in Counter(s).most_common())
```

**Python #2.** One-liner. Counter + sort. This is **O(N\*logN)** time complexity and is not preferred.
```
class Solution:
    def frequencySort(self, s: str) -> str:
        # the character itself is also used in the sorting key function
		# to resolve cases with equal character frequencies
		return "".join(sorted(s, key=lambda c, cnt=Counter(s): (-cnt[c],c)))  
```

**C++ #1.** Count then construct.
```
class Solution 
{
public:
    string frequencySort(string s) 
    {
        unordered_map<char,int> cnt;
        for (char c : s) ++cnt[c];                    // [1] counting character frequencies

        set<pair<int,char>> pq;                       // [2] set can be used as a priority queue to
        for (auto[ch,c] : cnt) pq.insert({-c, ch});   //     sort characters using their frequencies

        string ss = "";                               // [3] finally, we iterate over (sorted) elements of the
        for (auto[c,ch] : pq)                         //     set and construct chunks of resulting string by
            ss += string(-c, ch);                     //     repeating each character according to its count

        return ss;
    }
};
```

**C++ #2.** Count + sort. A similarly slow solution as Python #2.
```
class Solution 
{
public:
    string frequencySort(string s) 
    {
        int cnt[128] = {0};
        for (char c : s) ++cnt[c];

        auto cmp = [&](char a, char b)
        {
            return cnt[a] > cnt[b] || (cnt[a] == cnt[b] && a < b); 
        };

        sort(s.begin(), s.end(), cmp);

        return s;
    }
};
```

