solutions.content:
The idea is straightforward:
1. Get char frequencies of the given string `s` as `unordered_map<char,int> freq`;
2. Sort `freq` by values (i.e., frequencies) as `map<int, string> sortFreq`;
3. Create final sorted string `res` from `sortFreq`.

**Time Complexity:** Obviously, steps 1 and 3 cost `O(N)` time. Step 2 costs `O(N logM)` time, where `M` is the distinct number of char frequencies in `s`. It is easy to derive that `M = O(sqrt(N))`, so the overall time complexity is `O(N logN)`.

**Space Complexity:** Obviously, Step 3 to create the final string uses `O(N)` space no matter what algorithm you are choosing. Let's look at only Steps 1 and 2.
* `freq.size()` is number of distinct chars in `s` (worst case `O(char set size)`);
* `sortFreq.size()` is number of distinct char frequencies in `s` (worst case `O(sqrt(N))`).

Note that both of those sizes above could be much less than `N` (i.e., `s.size()`).
```
    string frequencySort(string& s) {
      // get char frequencies of s
      unordered_map<char,int> freq; for (char c:s) freq[c]++;
      // sort frequencies
      map<int, string> sortFreq; for (auto& p:freq) sortFreq[p.second] += p.first;

      string res; // create sorted string
      for (auto it = sortFreq.rbegin(); it != sortFreq.rend(); ++it)
        for (char c:it->second) res.append(it->first, c);
      return res;
    }
```

