# Approach
- Declare string ans to store the sorted string.
- Declare charFrequency unordered map and count the frequency of each character in the string.
- Store the frequencies and characters in a vector of pairs freqPairs.
- Sort vector of pairs in descending order based on frequencies using the sort function and the greater comparator.
- Construct the sorted string by iterating over freqPairs and appending the characters to ans based on their frequencies.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlogn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
string frequencySort(string s) {
    string ans = "";
    unordered_map<char, int> charFrequency;

    // Count the frequency of each character
    for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
        charFrequency[s[i]]++;
    }

    // Store the characters and their frequencies in a vector of pairs
    vector<pair<int, char>> freqPairs;
    for (auto it : charFrequency) {
        freqPairs.push_back(make_pair(it.second, it.first));
    }

    // Sort the vector in descending order based on frequencies
    sort(freqPairs.begin(), freqPairs.end(), greater<pair<int, char>>());

    // Construct the sorted string based on the sorted frequencies
    for (auto it : freqPairs) {
        for (int i = 0; i < it.first; i++) {
            ans += it.second;
        }
    }

    return ans;
}
};    

```
